  "summary": "In June 1935, Captain Arthur Hastings returns to London from a ranch in South America to attend to personal matters. Upon his arrival, he visits his old friend, Hercule Poirot, who has relocated to a modern, geometrically symmetrical service apartment in London. During their meeting, Hastings notices that Poirot appears younger and has darker hair; Poirot reveals he has been using a hair color restorer called \"Regenerate.\"\n\nThe two friends discuss Poirot's retirement. While Poirot claims to have switched to growing zucchinis, he admits he cannot resist difficult murder cases to keep his \"little gray cells\" active. Poirot mentions that he recently narrowly escaped a situation where he almost got killed due to a killer's carelessness. He tells Hastings that he considers Hastings a \"lucky charm\" and believes it is Hastings's fate to stand by his side to prevent him from making the \"unpardonable mistake\" of ignoring the obvious.\n\nThe conversation shifts when Poirot presents Hastings with a typed letter on thick white notepaper. The letter is signed by \"ABC\" and challenges Poirot to solve a mystery that baffled the British police, warning him to \"watch out for Andover\" on the twenty-first of the month. The envelope is postmarked London WC 1. While Hastings initially dismisses the sender as a \"nutcase,\" Poirot treats the communication with serious concern.",
